>>17406871
There's a multitude of reasons but some of the major ones are:
No mythological basis.
In the western literary canon there aren't really any myths, legends or folk tales that could be interpreted as /hmofa/.
Meanwhile Beauty and the Beast looms large.

Preconceived notions of gender roles and relations.
In the west men are commonly associated with base or beastly qualities whereas women are seen as the "more human" sex.
Reversing this dichotomy, if only on a surface level, does not come naturally as a result.

The character of the average furfag.
Among the people who do like anthros, misanthropy and self hatred are common.
Thus the majority of niche content creators in the west do not draw humans, as anthros are just an outlet to ignore their own flaws.

I've been adding "the west" to the end of these statements because we can, as is often the case, look to the land of the rising sun to how things could be different.
While true anthros there are rare for entirely unrelated reasons, stories with human male non-human female relationships are much more common because there's a strong mythological/literary basis for it, attitudes towards gender roles are different (among media consuming young men) and furry culture there has totally different origin points and a different less -sona focused character.
